story.title: Falco - Episode 7

messages.text: Investigation: Day 7
The following is a transcript of an interview between Agent Falco, Lynette Dixon, and Darrence Dixon, recorded June 26, 4:19 PM.
Thanks for coming in again, Mr. and Mrs. Dixon.
I can assure you we‚Äôre doing all we can to find your daughter.
Is this about her computer?
Did you find something?
Damn it, I should‚Äôve checked it sooner.
I completely forgot in all the commotion.
I should‚Äôve checked the tracker ‚Äî I never really looked.
She didn‚Äôt seem to use her computer all that much.
Well, she did use it prior to her disappearance.
I know this isn‚Äôt an easy question, but I have to ask.
Is it possible that your daughter was sexually active?
Absolutely not.
Premarital sex is a sin ‚Äî she knows that.
She‚Äôs a good girl, detective.
Wait, what is this about?
Tell us what you found on the computer.
Libby had been searching the Internet for information about pregnancy.
Pregnancy?
She must have been doing a project for school.
She was just doing research for health class.
You can ask her friend, Rachel ‚Äî they were working on an anatomy project together.
But these searches were dated early to mid-June‚Äî
The school year ended in May.
Our daughter was not sexually active, Agent Falco.
Darrence bangs his fist onto the table, startling Lynette.
I won‚Äôt allow you to tarnish her reputation with your baseless accusations.
I accessed her deleted text messages.
She didn‚Äôt want you to know she was seeing someone, sir.
I don‚Äôt appreciate this line of questioning, detective. I‚Äôm done here.
Darrence, wait.
Darrence storms out of the interview room as Lynette dissolves into sobs.
Please, Miss Falco.
Please help us find her.
I‚Äôm doing all I can, Mrs. Dixon, but I need your cooperation.
Do I have permission to access Libby‚Äôs medical records?
To see if she‚Äôs pregnant?
To see if I can get to the bottom of this whole thing.
Of course, yes ‚Äî whatever you need.
Libby had also searched the Internet for ‚Äúlegal age for abortion.‚Äù
Could she have been afraid of Darrence‚Äôs reaction if she were pregnant?
Libby couldn‚Äôt be pregnant, detective‚Äî
And even if she were, she‚Äôd never consider abortion. She‚Äôs very pro-life‚Äî
We all are.
Darrence seems pretty upset about a possible pregnancy.
Let‚Äôs say he found something out before her disappearance‚Ä¶
Could he have harmed your daughter?
Absolutely not.
Lynette composes herself and shakes her head in defense of her husband.
He doesn‚Äôt believe in violence.
Blessed are the peacemakers, for they shall be called sons of God.
Does Darrence believe in corporal punishment, perhaps?
Spare the rod, spoil the child?
Libby‚Äôs too old for spankings, detective.
So how do you think your husband would‚Äôve disciplined her?
You mean, if she were pregnant?
He would‚Äôve kicked her out of the house.
His roof, his rules ‚Äî but he never would‚Äôve hurt her, Miss Falco.
And how would you describe Libby‚Äôs feelings toward your husband?
Do you think Libby‚Äôs afraid of her father?
I suppose she could‚Äôve been scared of the repercussions‚Ä¶
But she would‚Äôve told me if she were pregnant‚Äî
Confided in me.
And I would‚Äôve helped her.
Behind your husband‚Äôs back?
Lynette looks down at the floor, dabbing at her eyes with a tissue.
If necessary, yes.
She‚Äôs my daughter, detective. I would‚Äôve taken care of it.
The sin would be mine.
You would‚Äôve gotten her an abortion?
I don‚Äôt know ‚Äî but I could never let her sleep on the streets.
Could Libby have confided in her sister, Anna Mae?
Was Anna Mae too afraid to tell us something?
I don‚Äôt know.
They used to be so close before Anna Mae starting spending all her time with that boyfriend of hers.
Jimmy Fitz?
Yeah. To be honest, I was a little relieved when they broke up a few weeks ago.
Relieved?
Don‚Äôt tell her I said so, please.
She‚Äôs heartbroken over Jimmy.
But it‚Äôs not healthy to be so invested so young.
She‚Äôs only nineteen, you know.
Besides, Darrence wasn‚Äôt very fond of Jimmy.
How come?
He got a DUI when he was 18. Darrence didn‚Äôt like that.
I think Jimmy spent some time in jail before he moved to Cedar Creek.
Darrence said he‚Äôd forgiven Jimmy of his transgression, of course.
But I think Darrence still held it against him.
Can you think of any other reasons why your husband didn‚Äôt approve of their relationship?
Maybe because Jimmy‚Äôs broken up with Anna Mae so many times.
She‚Äôs had some ongoing issues because of him, you know.
But this time he seems to be gone for good.
So the girls drifted apart due to Anna Mae‚Äôs boy troubles?
Well, Libby had her own troubles with Duke, of course.
Of course.
Lynette blows her nose, and Agent Falco hands her another tissue from the box.
Is it okay if we take a look at Libby‚Äôs bedroom, Mrs. Dixon?
But Sheriff Simmons searched her room after we reported her missing.
I think it‚Äôs worth checking out one more time‚Äî
If there‚Äôs incriminating evidence against his son in Libby‚Äôs bedroom, Sheriff Simmons may have ignored it.
Okay, of course ‚Äî whatever you need.
Deputy Decker will be by in the morning, then.
Get some rest tonight, okay?
I‚Äôve got some other leads to follow up on.
Speaking of which, has Libby ever been to Newbury, Tennessee?
I don‚Äôt think so.
Have you ever heard of an Internet cafe called Wired?
No. Did you find something out about my daughter?
Lynette perks up, anxious for news.
Has she been seen at that cafe?
Should we go there and see?
I‚Äôm looking into it, Mrs. Dixon. I‚Äôll be in touch soon, okay?
Lynette sinks back in her chair, defeated.
Thank you, detective.
You‚Äôre very welcome. Take care.
Investigation: Day 8
The following is a text message conversation between Agent Falco and Deputy Decker, initiated June 27, 7:37 AM.
How‚Äôs the search going, Deputy?
Peachy, Agent Falco. Literally.
What does that mean?
A tube of peach lip gloss busted all over Libby‚Äôs sock drawer.
I guess she hadn‚Äôt noticed yet.
Have you found anything helpful, Deputy Decker?
I found a few rubbers hidden in a pair of socks.
Condoms?
So it does seem like Libby was sexually active‚Ä¶
But I need to know if she‚Äôs actually pregnant.
Could she have run off to get an abortion, you think?
Possibly ‚Äî could be what the fake ID was for.
You have to be 18 to get an abortion without parental consent in Tennessee.
But she didn‚Äôt need to leave her car and cell phone behind for that.
Yeah.
Unless something went wrong, maybe?
What‚Äôs your theory, Deputy?
She acquires the fake ID to get the abortion.
She goes to the clinic, but they know it‚Äôs a fake.
The doctors there turn Libby away‚Ä¶
So she and Bronco have to take matters into their own hands.
Are you suggesting they tried to perform the abortion themselves, Decker?
Strangers things have happened, detective.
But say something DID go terribly wrong‚Ä¶
Libby‚Äôs death is accidental, but her boyfriend has to dispose of her body.
That‚Äôs what he does, and then he leaves her car and stuff behind.
Knifes the tire to make it look like a flat.
That way, it throws us off the scent ‚Äî we think she‚Äôs been abducted off of Route 12 or something.
Okay, but where did this coat-hanger abortion occur?
There was no blood in Room 201 of The Junction.
Could be they decided to do it elsewhere.
I don‚Äôt really know.
But Libby was seen by the clerk at Wired, correct?
After she disappeared.
Yeah, but witnesses mistake IDs all the time.
Certainly ‚Äî eyewitness testimony is notoriously unreliable.
It‚Äôs usually the worst kind of evidence.
But the clerk seemed so sure it was her.
He could‚Äôve been wrong. I could ask him again.
Okay. Thanks.
So is Bronco now our prime suspect?
I guess so.
But I‚Äôm not ruling out Duke either.
How come?
Say he found out about Libby‚Äôs pregnancy.
Assuming she‚Äôs pregnant.
Yeah. He‚Äôs pissed because she dumped him for this Bronco fella.
He finds out about the baby ‚Äî sends those texts calling her a slut.
Follows her to the motel.
Pulls her over on her way home.
Kills her.
And then dumps the body and stages the scene.
That‚Äôs also possible.
Or maybe Libby didn‚Äôt want to get an abortion‚Äî
Perhaps she felt pressured by Bronco.
A child would‚Äôve been evidence of their illicit affair.
Bronco could‚Äôve seen jail time for statutory rape.
So she changes her mind about the procedure and he kills her to hide the evidence of their relationship?
That‚Äôs pretty cold.
Like you said, stranger things have happened.
But what if the clerk at Wired really did see Libby?
Could she have run off to protect her unborn child?
So she‚Äôs hiding from Bronco then, right? Not Duke.
Maybe she‚Äôs hiding from both of them.
And she threatened you from the Internet cafe because she doesn‚Äôt want to be found.
Possibly. We should check out some nearby women‚Äôs shelters.
And talk to bus drivers and taxi cabs?
Yeah. She left her vehicle out on Route 12.
She had to get to the shelter somehow, if that‚Äôs where she went.
But could a scared, pregnant teen really pull something like that off?
Could she really vanish into thin air without any help or resources?
I don‚Äôt know.
But I found something under her pillow.
A copy of the mystery novel ‚ÄúGhost Girl.‚Äù
Is that relevant, Deputy?
Page 68 is dog-eared.
That seems to be the page where the heroine disappears.
Excuse me?
‚ÄúGhost Girl‚Äù is about a teen who goes missing. Coincidence?
I don‚Äôt know.
It could be.
I guess it‚Äôs a pretty popular book ‚Äî Cate has a copy.
It‚Äôs eerie, but let‚Äôs look for something a little more concrete.
What about Libby‚Äôs bedroom? Anything missing?
Is there any evidence that she packed her things?
Not that I can see.
Her stuffed pig‚Äôs still here.
Lynette doesn‚Äôt think she‚Äôd have left without Napoleon.
Napoleon? Like the pig from ‚ÄúAnimal Farm?‚Äù
I don‚Äôt know. I haven‚Äôt read ‚ÄúAnimal Farm.‚Äù
Keep looking around, Deputy.
I‚Äôm going to check out Scoops.
Sounds good. I‚Äôll let you know if I find anything else.
Okay, thanks, Decker.
No problem, boss.
The following is an audio call from Jason Spelling, the clerk at Wired, to Agent Falco, placed June 27, 1:13 PM.
Falco.
Hi, Detective Falco. This is Jason Spelling from the Wired cafe. I talked to a deputy a few days ago, and he left your business card here‚Äî
Said I should call you if I saw that chick again.
Are you talking about Libby Dixon?
Yeah, I guess. That girl from the missing poster he showed me.
And you told Deputy Decker you‚Äôd seen her before, right?
Yeah, she‚Äôs been in a couple times.
I mean, she had giant sunglasses on, but I remember what she looks like.
So you‚Äôre calling to tell me she‚Äôs been in again?
Well, yeah, I mean ‚Äî she‚Äôs here now. Same sunglasses, same big boobs.
She‚Äôs there right now?
Yeah, she‚Äôs on Terminal A3.
Describe her to me, Mr. Spelling.
Uh, she‚Äôs like medium-height, I guess. Tan skin. Totally stacked. She‚Äôs got brown hair‚Äî
I don‚Äôt know what color her eyes are ‚Äòcause of the sunglasses.
What is she wearing, sir?
Jeans and a tee shirt. She‚Äôs got a sweater tied around her waist, prob‚Äôly brought it ‚Äòcause they blast the AC in here.
Is she with anyone? Have you seen her talking to anybody?
No, she‚Äôs here by herself.
She looks just like the girl on the poster. She‚Äôs definitely the chick I saw in here before.
Are you sure?
Totally. She acts all nervous when she‚Äôs here, like she‚Äôs tweaked out on caffeine or something‚Ä¶
But she never orders any coffee.
What do you mean, she‚Äôs acting nervous?
I don‚Äôt know ‚Äî she just kinda seems on edge, you know?
Okay, I‚Äôm about half an hour out of Newbury. I need you to stall her if she tries to leave, all right?
Stall her? Like how?
Tell her there‚Äôs a problem with her payment or something.
You pay for your time block before you log on, detective.
Like, the terminal won‚Äôt let you get on the ‚Äònet ‚Äòtil you insert cash or swipe your card.
Okay, well, chat her up, then.
Excuse me?
Talk to her, flirt with her ‚Äî just act natural, okay?
Uh, okay.
Don‚Äôt tell her that you recognize her, got it?
Yeah, I got it.
I‚Äôm leaving right now. Thanks for your help, Mr. Spelling.
All right. See you soon.
The following is a communication from ‚ÄúConnor Mason‚Äù to Agent Falco on the Facespace messaging app, sent June 27, 1:20 PM.
You need to stop asking questions, bitch.
Let the Dixon case be.
Tell me who this is.
No.
Is this Libby?
No.
You won‚Äôt get in trouble, okay?
Your family just wants you home safe.
I told you I‚Äôm not Libby.
Okay. Then who are you?
Your worst nightmare.
I know where you sleep, lady.
You need to stop.
Is Libby okay?
Do you know where she is?
You‚Äôre not getting it, are you?
Tell me if she‚Äôs still alive.
Tell me your real name.
49 Union Street, Cedar Creek, TN, 37099.
Is that the address for The Winchester?
How do you know which hotel I‚Äôm staying at?
Have you been following me?
How are you connected to the Dixon case?
Hello?
Connor Mason is offline.
The following is a text message conversation between Agent Falco and Deputy Decker, initiated June 27, 1:52 PM.
I‚Äôm out at Wired, Decker.
But the girl we‚Äôre looking for isn‚Äôt here.
That‚Äôs some rotten luck.
The clerk said she left when he was in the bathroom.
So much for stalling her.
And nobody else here seems to have noticed much about her.
I‚Äôm headed back to Cedar Creek ‚Äî we can talk more then.
I was just about to call you, actually.
You might want to stop off at Stark‚Äôs Quarry on your way back, detective.
It‚Äôs a few miles out of town.
Stark‚Äôs Quarry?
Why do I need to stop there?
That‚Äôs why I was about to call you.
A swimmer just contacted 911 from that location.
Okay. How come?
To tell us what he found out floating in the water‚Äî
The dead body of a young girl.
